{"id":"nlin/0411060","submitter":"Guido Ventura","authors":"Francois Holtz, Sascha Lenne, Guido Ventura, Francesco Vetere, Philipp\n  Wolf","title":"Non-linear deformation and break up of enclaves in a rhyolitic magma: a\n  case study from Lipari Island (Southern Italy)","comments":"to be printed on Geophysical Research Letters","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1029/2004GL021590","report-no":null,"categories":"nlin.CD","license":null,"abstract":"  A dome from Lipari Island (Southern Italy) consists of 12 vol. percent of\ncircular, elongated and folded latitic enclaves hosted in a rhyolitic matrix.\nThe dm- to cm-scale enclaves are more deformed than the mm-scale blobs. The\ncritical value of the ratio between the viscous forces, which allow deformation\nand eventually break up blobs of latitic magma, and the interfacial tension\nforces is larger than 0.29. The Reynolds number is < 5.3. The equivalent radius\nand the axial ratio of the enclaves follow power-law distributions. This\nfeature suggests that the break up and stretching of magmas are non-linear,\nscale-invariant, probably cyclic processes. The coexistence of enclaves of\ndifferent shape and the self-similar size distributions suggest that chaotic\nadvection plays a major role in the formation of mingled magmas. Caution must\nbe used when measuring the finite strain from enclave shapes because they may\nbreak apart during the deformation.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 29 Nov 2004 11:21:57 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-26"}
